  "text": "All sensor nodes are uniformly and randomly distributed in a sensing field. A powerful Sink node is deployed to gather sensing readings from the whole network. All sensor nodes have the identical communication radius and communicate with distant nodes hop by hop. Periodically, sensor nodes generate environmental readings which evolve over time, and transmit these readings to Sink node via a data collection tree (DCT). In the multihop scenario, a DCT is requisite and can be built in a distributed manner. For instance, by circulating a tree formation message originated by Sink and making use of a min-hop parent selection strategy or other algorithms used for constructing maximum-lifetime data gathering tree [CITATION_1] . After building the DCT each sensor node learns its unique node in the DCT, and maintains a list of its direct children nodes in DCT, ℎ . Furthermore, each sensor node maintains a queue to store the most recent sensing readings and keeps tracking of the average value of those data. The size of data queue would not be very great so that no extra storage space is needed to add for current sensor node platform. By exploiting the readings in queue, each sensor node can learn an AR model using least-square method. Similar to PAQ [CITATION_2] , we also adopt a narrow prediction window, that is, = 3, to neglect the impact of non-stationary physical environment. This setting also makes the AR model simple and light-weight enough for resource-limited sensor nodes. To cope with dynamical environment, for example, the rapid temperature change around the 800th epoch in Figure 3 , we adopt the model monitoring algorithm of PAQ to maintain an accurate and dynamic local AR model for each sensor node. A sensor node generally relearns its AR model using the latest data in queue if the times of the prediction error beyond error threshold within consecutive Λ epochs exceeds a predefined threshold ].",
